*A foolish consistency is the hobgoblin of little minds, adored by little s=
tatesmen and philosophers and divines.*
=E2=80=94 Ralph Waldo Emerson, =E2=80=9CSelf-Reliance=E2=80=9D, Essays: Fir=
st Series, 1841

*In the beginning was the Word, and the Word was with God, and the Word was=
 God.*
=E2=80=94 John 1:1, King James Version

A recurring theme on Stratechery is that the only technology analogous to t=
he Internet=E2=80=99s impact on humanity is the printing press: Johannes Gu=
tenberg=E2=80=99s invention in 1440 drastically reduced the marginal cost o=
f printing books, dramatically increasing the amount of information that co=
uld be disseminated.

Of course you still had to actually write the book, and set the movable typ=
e in the printing press; this, though, meant we had the first version of th=
e classic tech business model: the cost to create a book was fixed, but the=
 potential revenue from printing a book =E2=80=94 and overall profitability=
 =E2=80=94=C2=A0was a function of how many copies you could sell. Every add=
itional copy increased the leverage on the up-front costs of producing the =
book in the first place, improving the overall profitability; this, by exte=
nsion, meant there were strong incentives to produce popular books.

This set off a number of changes that transformed history. Before the print=
ing press:

* The Bible was the province of the Catholic Church; it was only available =
in Latin and laboriously reproduced by monks. In practice this meant that t=
he Catholic Church was the source of religious authority throughout Europe.
* Europe didn=E2=80=99t have any nation-states as we think of them today; t=
he relevant political authority was some combination of city-states and feu=
dal lords.
* The linguistic landscape was extremely diverse: Latin was the language of=
 the church, while larger regions might have a dominant dialect, which itse=
lf could differ from local dialects only spoken in a limited geographic are=
a.

The printing press was a direct assault on that last point: because it stil=
l cost money to produce a book, it made sense to print books in the most do=
minant dialect in the region; because books were compelling it behooved peo=
ple to learn to read that dominant dialect. This, over time, would mean tha=
t the dominant dialect would increase its dominance in a virtuous cycle =E2=
=80=94=C2=A0network effects, in other words.

Books, meanwhile, transmitted culture, building affinity between neighborin=
g city states; it took decades and, in some cases, centuries, but over time=
 Europe settled into a new equilibrium of distinct nation-states, with thei=
r own languages. Critical to this reorganization was point one: the printin=
g press meant everyone could have access to the Bible, or read pamphlets ch=
allenging the Catholic Church. Martin Luther=E2=80=99s 95 Theses was one su=
ch example: printing presses spread the challenge to papal authority far an=
d wide precisely because it was so incendiary =E2=80=94 that was good for b=
usiness. The Protestant Reformation that followed didn=E2=80=99t just have =
theological implications: it also provided the religious underpinnings for =
those distinct nation states, which legitimized their rule with their own n=
ational churches.

Of course history didn=E2=80=99t end there: the apotheosis of the Reformati=
on=E2=80=99s influence on nation states was the United States, which set ou=
t an explicit guarantee that there would be no official government religion=
 at all; every person was free to serve God in whatever way they pleased. T=
his freedom was itself emblematic of what America represented in its most i=
dealized form: 1 ( #fn1-12430 ) endless frontier and the freedom to pursue =
one=E2=80=99s God-given rights of =E2=80=9CLife, Liberty and the pursuit of=
 Happiness.=E2=80=9D

Aggregation Theory
------------------

